  <h2>What is DADGAD?</h2>
  <p>
    DADGAD is the open, drony tuning behind much of Celtic guitar, "Kashmir,"
    and modern fingerstyle. From standard, three strings move: the low E drops
    to D, the B drops to A, and the high E drops to D — giving D–A–D–G–A–D.
    Strummed open it rings as a suspended chord that's neither major nor minor,
    which is exactly why players love it.
  </p>
  <h2>How to tune to DADGAD</h2>
  <p>
    Tap start. Strings 6, 2, and 1 come down a whole step (the tuner will say
    "too high — loosen"); strings 5, 4, and 3 stay put — pluck them anyway to
    confirm. Note that in DADGAD the G and A strings are only a whole step
    apart, so if the tuner seems unsure which of the two you're playing, tap
    the right one below the needle.
  </p>
